  "prompt": "How do I configure an SDN controller as a master and slave role in OpenDaylight, Floodlight, Ryu or Beacon?",
  "response": "I'll provide configuration guidance for configuring master/slave roles in some popular SDN controllers:\n\n1. OpenDaylight (ODL):\n```java\n// In clustering configuration\nClusterAdmin clusterAdmin = ...;\nclusterAdmin.setControllerRole(ControllerRole.MASTER);\n// Or for slave role\nclusterAdmin.setControllerRole(ControllerRole.SLAVE);\n```\n\n2. Floodlight:\n```java\n// Floodlight doesn't natively support master/slave roles directly\n// Clustering is typically handled through external load balancers\nIFloodlightProviderService.setRole(Role.MASTER);\nIFloodlightProviderService.setRole(Role.SLAVE);\n```\n\n3. Ryu:\n```python\n# In Ryu controller application\nfrom ryu.controller import handler\nfrom ryu.controller import ofp_event\n\nclass MyController(app_manager.RyuApp):\n    def set_controller_role(self, role):\n        # Configure role in OpenFlow handshake\n        msg = ofp_event.OFPRoleRequest(\n            datapath,\n    \t    role=role  # MASTER or SLAVE\n        )\n        datapath.send_msg(msg)\n```\n\n4. Beacon:\n```java\n// Beacon role configuration\nIBeaconControllerService controllerService;\ncontrollerService.setControllerRole(ControllerRole.MASTER);\n```\n\nGeneral considerations:\n- Verify your specific controller version\n- Check clustering/high availability configurations\n- Implement appropriate role negotiation mechanisms\n\nBest practice is to consult each controller's specific documentation for precise implementation details.",
